{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585181"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14928"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0,0.06,0.83,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7616"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacterial antigens is most likely responsible for triggering rheumatic fever through molecular mimicry?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcal protein A","Mycobacterial lipoarabinomannan","Lipopolysaccharide O antigen","Streptococcal M protein","Polyribosylribitol phosphate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERheumatic fever is an inflammatory disease that can develop after an infection with \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, commonly known as Group A Streptococcus. It typically occurs 2-3 weeks after untreated streptococcal pharyngitis. The disease is characterised by fever, migratory polyarthritis, carditis, and sometimes a rash or subcutaneous nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcal M protein\u003C/strong\u003E is a virulence factor of \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E that shares structural similarities with cardiac myosin and other tissue proteins. This molecular mimicry triggers an autoimmune response where antibodies and T cells directed against the M protein cross-react with human tissues, particularly heart tissue, leading to carditis and other manifestations of rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcal protein A\u003C/strong\u003E is a cell wall component of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E that binds immunoglobulin. While it has immunological effects, it is not associated with rheumatic fever or molecular mimicry with cardiac tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterial lipoarabinomannan\u003C/strong\u003E is a cell wall component of mycobacteria that plays a role in immune modulation but is not associated with molecular mimicry leading to rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipopolysaccharide O antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is found in gram-negative bacteria like \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E. While it can trigger strong immune responses, it is not associated with rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyribosylribitol phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is the capsular antigen of \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E type b. It is important in vaccine development but is not associated with molecular mimicry leading to rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group A Streptococcus (S. pyogenes) M protein shares molecular mimicry with cardiac tissue, leading to autoimmune damage in rheumatic fever.","Molecular mimicry between bacterial and host antigens is a key mechanism in post-infectious autoimmune conditions.","Rheumatic fever typically develops 2-3 weeks after untreated streptococcal pharyngitis."],"references":["Carapetis JR, Beaton A, Cunningham MW, Guilherme L, Karthikeyan G, Mayosi BM, Sable C, Steer A, Wilson N, Wyber R, Z\u00fchlke L. Acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Jan 14;2:15084. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2015.84. PMID: 27188830; PMCID: PMC5810582.","Chowdhury MDS, Koziatek CA, Rajnik M. Acute Rheumatic Fever. [Updated 2023 Aug 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK594238/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T15:44:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T15:45:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7616"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},